61/// An adjustment to be made to the temporary created when emitting a
62/// reference binding, which accesses a particular subobject of that temporary.
63struct SubobjectAdjustment {
64 enum {
65 DerivedToBaseAdjustment,
66 FieldAdjustment,
67 MemberPointerAdjustment
68 } Kind;
69
70 struct DTB {
71 const CastExpr *BasePath;
72 const CXXRecordDecl *DerivedClass;
73 };
74
75 struct P {
76 const MemberPointerType *MPT;
77 Expr *RHS;
78 };
79
80 union {
81 struct DTB DerivedToBase;
82 FieldDecl *Field;
83 struct P Ptr;
84 };
85
86 SubobjectAdjustment(const CastExpr *BasePath,
87 const CXXRecordDecl *DerivedClass)
88 : Kind(DerivedToBaseAdjustment) {
89 DerivedToBase.BasePath = BasePath;
90 DerivedToBase.DerivedClass = DerivedClass;
91 }
92
93 SubobjectAdjustment(FieldDecl *Field)
94 : Kind(FieldAdjustment) {
95 this->Field = Field;
96 }
97
98 SubobjectAdjustment(const MemberPointerType *MPT, Expr *RHS)
99 : Kind(MemberPointerAdjustment) {
100 this->Ptr.MPT = MPT;
101 this->Ptr.RHS = RHS;
102 }
103};

105/// This represents one expression. Note that Expr's are subclasses of Stmt.
106/// This allows an expression to be transparently used any place a Stmt is
107/// required.
108class Expr : public ValueStmt {
109 QualType TR;
110
111public:
112 Expr() = delete;
113 Expr(const Expr&) = delete;
114 Expr(Expr &&) = delete;
115 Expr &operator=(const Expr&) = delete;
116 Expr &operator=(Expr&&) = delete;
117
118protected:
119 Expr(StmtClass SC, QualType T, ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK,
120 bool TD, bool VD, bool ID, bool ContainsUnexpandedParameterPack)
121 : ValueStmt(SC)
122 {
123 ExprBits.TypeDependent = TD;
124 ExprBits.ValueDependent = VD;
125 ExprBits.InstantiationDependent = ID;
126 ExprBits.ValueKind = VK;
127 ExprBits.ObjectKind = OK;
128 assert(ExprBits.ObjectKind == OK && "truncated kind");
129 ExprBits.ContainsUnexpandedParameterPack = ContainsUnexpandedParameterPack;
130 setType(T);
131 }
132
133 /// Construct an empty expression.
134 explicit Expr(StmtClass SC, EmptyShell) : ValueStmt(SC) { }
135
136public:
137 QualType getType() const { return TR; }
138 void setType(QualType t) {
139 // In C++, the type of an expression is always adjusted so that it
140 // will not have reference type (C++ [expr]p6). Use
141 // QualType::getNonReferenceType() to retrieve the non-reference
142 // type. Additionally, inspect Expr::isLvalue to determine whether
143 // an expression that is adjusted in this manner should be
144 // considered an lvalue.
145 assert((t.isNull() || !t->isReferenceType()) &&
146 "Expressions can't have reference type");
147
148 TR = t;
149 }

151 /// isValueDependent - Determines whether this expression is
152 /// value-dependent (C++ [temp.dep.constexpr]). For example, the
153 /// array bound of "Chars" in the following example is
154 /// value-dependent.
155 /// @code
156 /// template<int Size, char (&Chars)[Size]> struct meta_string;
157 /// @endcode
158 bool isValueDependent() const { return ExprBits.ValueDependent; }
159
160 /// Set whether this expression is value-dependent or not.
161 void setValueDependent(bool VD) {
162 ExprBits.ValueDependent = VD;
163 }
164
165 /// isTypeDependent - Determines whether this expression is
166 /// type-dependent (C++ [temp.dep.expr]), which means that its type
167 /// could change from one template instantiation to the next. For
168 /// example, the expressions "x" and "x + y" are type-dependent in
169 /// the following code, but "y" is not type-dependent:
170 /// @code
171 /// template<typename T>
172 /// void add(T x, int y) {
173 /// x + y;
174 /// }
175 /// @endcode
176 bool isTypeDependent() const { return ExprBits.TypeDependent; }
177
178 /// Set whether this expression is type-dependent or not.
179 void setTypeDependent(bool TD) {
180 ExprBits.TypeDependent = TD;
181 }
182
183 /// Whether this expression is instantiation-dependent, meaning that
184 /// it depends in some way on a template parameter, even if neither its type
185 /// nor (constant) value can change due to the template instantiation.
186 ///
187 /// In the following example, the expression \c sizeof(sizeof(T() + T())) is
188 /// instantiation-dependent (since it involves a template parameter \c T), but
189 /// is neither type- nor value-dependent, since the type of the inner
190 /// \c sizeof is known (\c std::size_t) and therefore the size of the outer
191 /// \c sizeof is known.
192 ///
193 /// \code
194 /// template<typename T>
195 /// void f(T x, T y) {
196 /// sizeof(sizeof(T() + T());
197 /// }
198 /// \endcode
199 ///
200 bool isInstantiationDependent() const {
201 return ExprBits.InstantiationDependent;
202 }
203
204 /// Set whether this expression is instantiation-dependent or not.
205 void setInstantiationDependent(bool ID) {
206 ExprBits.InstantiationDependent = ID;
207 }
208
209 /// Whether this expression contains an unexpanded parameter
210 /// pack (for C++11 variadic templates).
211 ///
212 /// Given the following function template:
213 ///
214 /// \code
215 /// template<typename F, typename ...Types>
216 /// void forward(const F &f, Types &&...args) {
217 /// f(static_cast<Types&&>(args)...);
218 /// }
219 /// \endcode
220 ///
221 /// The expressions \c args and \c static_cast<Types&&>(args) both
222 /// contain parameter packs.
223 bool containsUnexpandedParameterPack() const {
224 return ExprBits.ContainsUnexpandedParameterPack;
225 }
226
227 /// Set the bit that describes whether this expression
228 /// contains an unexpanded parameter pack.
229 void setContainsUnexpandedParameterPack(bool PP = true) {
230 ExprBits.ContainsUnexpandedParameterPack = PP;
231 }

237 /// isUnusedResultAWarning - Return true if this immediate expression should

245 /// isLValue - True if this expression is an "l-value" according to
246 /// the rules of the current language. C and C++ give somewhat
247 /// different rules for this concept, but in general, the result of
248 /// an l-value expression identifies a specific object whereas the
249 /// result of an r-value expression is a value detached from any
250 /// specific storage.
251 ///
252 /// C++11 divides the concept of "r-value" into pure r-values
253 /// ("pr-values") and so-called expiring values ("x-values"), which
254 /// identify specific objects that can be safely cannibalized for
255 /// their resources. This is an unfortunate abuse of terminology on
256 /// the part of the C++ committee. In Clang, when we say "r-value",
257 /// we generally mean a pr-value.
258 bool isLValue() const { return getValueKind() == VK_LValue; }
259 bool isRValue() const { return getValueKind() == VK_RValue; }
260 bool isXValue() const { return getValueKind() == VK_XValue; }
261 bool isGLValue() const { return getValueKind() != VK_RValue; }
262

268 LV_InvalidExpression,
269 LV_InvalidMessageExpression,

271 LV_SubObjCPropertySetting,
272 LV_ClassTemporary,
273 LV_ArrayTemporary
274 };
275 /// Reasons why an expression might not be an l-value.
276 LValueClassification ClassifyLValue(ASTContext &Ctx) const;

297 /// isModifiableLvalue - C99 6.3.2.1: an lvalue that does not have array type,
298 /// does not have an incomplete type, does not have a const-qualified type,
299 /// and if it is a structure or union, does not have any member (including,
300 /// recursively, any member or element of all contained aggregates or unions)
301 /// with a const-qualified type.
302 ///
303 /// \param Loc [in,out] - A source location which *may* be filled
304 /// in with the location of the expression making this a
305 /// non-modifiable lvalue, if specified.
306 isModifiableLvalueResult

309 /// The return type of classify(). Represents the C++11 expression
310 /// taxonomy.
311 class Classification {
312 public:
313 /// The various classification results. Most of these mean prvalue.
314 enum Kinds {
315 CL_LValue,
316 CL_XValue,
317 CL_Function, // Functions cannot be lvalues in C.
318 CL_Void, // Void cannot be an lvalue in C.
319 CL_AddressableVoid, // Void expression whose address can be taken in C.
320 CL_DuplicateVectorComponents, // A vector shuffle with dupes.
321 CL_MemberFunction, // An expression referring to a member function
322 CL_SubObjCPropertySetting,
323 CL_ClassTemporary, // A temporary of class type, or subobject thereof.
324 CL_ArrayTemporary, // A temporary of array type.
325 CL_ObjCMessageRValue, // ObjC message is an rvalue
326 CL_PRValue // A prvalue for any other reason, of any other type
327 };
328 /// The results of modification testing.
329 enum ModifiableType {
330 CM_Untested, // testModifiable was false.
331 CM_Modifiable,
332 CM_RValue, // Not modifiable because it's an rvalue
333 CM_Function, // Not modifiable because it's a function; C++ only
334 CM_LValueCast, // Same as CM_RValue, but indicates GCC cast-as-lvalue ext
335 CM_NoSetterProperty,// Implicit assignment to ObjC property without setter
336 CM_ConstQualified,
337 CM_ConstQualifiedField,
338 CM_ConstAddrSpace,
339 CM_ArrayType,
340 CM_IncompleteType
341 };
342
343 private:
344 friend class Expr;
345
346 unsigned short Kind;
347 unsigned short Modifiable;
348
349 explicit Classification(Kinds k, ModifiableType m)
350 : Kind(k), Modifiable(m)
351 {}
352
353 public:
354 Classification() {}
355
356 Kinds getKind() const { return static_cast<Kinds>(Kind); }
357 ModifiableType getModifiable() const {
358 assert(Modifiable != CM_Untested && "Did not test for modifiability.");
359 return static_cast<ModifiableType>(Modifiable);
360 }
361 bool isLValue() const { return Kind == CL_LValue; }
362 bool isXValue() const { return Kind == CL_XValue; }
363 bool isGLValue() const { return Kind <= CL_XValue; }
364 bool isPRValue() const { return Kind >= CL_Function; }
365 bool isRValue() const { return Kind >= CL_XValue; }
366 bool isModifiable() const { return getModifiable() == CM_Modifiable; }
367
368 /// Create a simple, modifiably lvalue
369 static Classification makeSimpleLValue() {
370 return Classification(CL_LValue, CM_Modifiable);
371 }
372
373 };
374 /// Classify - Classify this expression according to the C++11
375 /// expression taxonomy.
376 ///
377 /// C++11 defines ([basic.lval]) a new taxonomy of expressions to replace the
378 /// old lvalue vs rvalue. This function determines the type of expression this
379 /// is. There are three expression types:
380 /// - lvalues are classical lvalues as in C++03.
381 /// - prvalues are equivalent to rvalues in C++03.
382 /// - xvalues are expressions yielding unnamed rvalue references, e.g. a
383 /// function returning an rvalue reference.
384 /// lvalues and xvalues are collectively referred to as glvalues, while
385 /// prvalues and xvalues together form rvalues.
386 Classification Classify(ASTContext &Ctx) const {
387 return ClassifyImpl(Ctx, nullptr);
388 }
389
390 /// ClassifyModifiable - Classify this expression according to the
391 /// C++11 expression taxonomy, and see if it is valid on the left side
392 /// of an assignment.
393 ///
394 /// This function extends classify in that it also tests whether the
395 /// expression is modifiable (C99 6.3.2.1p1).
396 /// \param Loc A source location that might be filled with a relevant location
397 /// if the expression is not modifiable.
398 Classification ClassifyModifiable(ASTContext &Ctx, SourceLocation &Loc) const{
399 return ClassifyImpl(Ctx, &Loc);
400 }

402 /// getValueKindForType - Given a formal return or parameter type,
403 /// give its value kind.
404 static ExprValueKind getValueKindForType(QualType T) {
405 if (const ReferenceType *RT = T->getAs<ReferenceType>())
406 return (isa<LValueReferenceType>(RT)
407 ? VK_LValue
408 : (RT->getPointeeType()->isFunctionType()
409 ? VK_LValue : VK_XValue));
410 return VK_RValue;
411 }
412
413 /// getValueKind - The value kind that this expression produces.
414 ExprValueKind getValueKind() const {
415 return static_cast<ExprValueKind>(ExprBits.ValueKind);
416 }
417
418 /// getObjectKind - The object kind that this expression produces.
419 /// Object kinds are meaningful only for expressions that yield an
420 /// l-value or x-value.
421 ExprObjectKind getObjectKind() const {
422 return static_cast<ExprObjectKind>(ExprBits.ObjectKind);
423 }
424
425 bool isOrdinaryOrBitFieldObject() const {
426 ExprObjectKind OK = getObjectKind();
427 return (OK == OK_Ordinary || OK == OK_BitField);
428 }
429
430 /// setValueKind - Set the value kind produced by this expression.
431 void setValueKind(ExprValueKind Cat) { ExprBits.ValueKind = Cat; }
432
433 /// setObjectKind - Set the object kind produced by this expression.
434 void setObjectKind(ExprObjectKind Cat) { ExprBits.ObjectKind = Cat; }

441 /// Returns true if this expression is a gl-value that
442 /// potentially refers to a bit-field.

445 /// an aspect of the value-kind type system.

448 /// If this expression refers to a bit-field, retrieve the
449 /// declaration of that bit-field.
450 ///
451 /// Note that this returns a non-null pointer in subtly different
452 /// places than refersToBitField returns true. In particular, this can
453 /// return a non-null pointer even for r-values loaded from
454 /// bit-fields, but it will return null for a conditional bit-field.
455 FieldDecl *getSourceBitField();

458 return const_cast<Expr*>(this)->getSourceBitField();

549 /// EvalStatus is a struct with detailed info about an evaluation in progress.
550 struct EvalStatus {
551 /// Whether the evaluated expression has side effects.
552 /// For example, (f() && 0) can be folded, but it still has side effects.
553 bool HasSideEffects;
554
555 /// Whether the evaluation hit undefined behavior.
556 /// For example, 1.0 / 0.0 can be folded to Inf, but has undefined behavior.
557 /// Likewise, INT_MAX + 1 can be folded to INT_MIN, but has UB.
558 bool HasUndefinedBehavior;
559
560 /// Diag - If this is non-null, it will be filled in with a stack of notes
561 /// indicating why evaluation failed (or why it failed to produce a constant
562 /// expression).
563 /// If the expression is unfoldable, the notes will indicate why it's not
564 /// foldable. If the expression is foldable, but not a constant expression,
565 /// the notes will describes why it isn't a constant expression. If the
566 /// expression *is* a constant expression, no notes will be produced.
567 SmallVectorImpl<PartialDiagnosticAt> *Diag;
568
569 EvalStatus()
570 : HasSideEffects(false), HasUndefinedBehavior(false), Diag(nullptr) {}
571
572 // hasSideEffects - Return true if the evaluated expression has
573 // side effects.
574 bool hasSideEffects() const {
575 return HasSideEffects;
576 }
577 };
578
579 /// EvalResult is a struct with detailed info about an evaluated expression.
580 struct EvalResult : EvalStatus {
581 /// Val - This is the value the expression can be folded to.
582 APValue Val;
583
584 // isGlobalLValue - Return true if the evaluated lvalue expression
585 // is global.
586 bool isGlobalLValue() const;
587 };

589 /// EvaluateAsRValue - Return true if this is a constant which we can fold to
590 /// an rvalue using any crazy technique (that has nothing to do with language
591 /// standards) that we want to, even if the expression has side-effects. If
592 /// this function returns true, it returns the folded constant in Result. If
593 /// the expression is a glvalue, an lvalue-to-rvalue conversion will be
594 /// applied.
595 bool EvaluateAsRValue(EvalResult &Result, const ASTContext &Ctx,
596 bool InConstantContext = false) const;
597
598 /// EvaluateAsBooleanCondition - Return true if this is a constant
599 /// which we can fold and convert to a boolean condition using
600 /// any crazy technique that we want to, even if the expression has
601 /// side-effects.
602 bool EvaluateAsBooleanCondition(bool &Result, const ASTContext &Ctx) const;

604 enum SideEffectsKind {
605 SE_NoSideEffects, ///< Strictly evaluate the expression.
606 SE_AllowUndefinedBehavior, ///< Allow UB that we can give a value, but not
607 ///< arbitrary unmodeled side effects.
608 SE_AllowSideEffects ///< Allow any unmodeled side effect.
609 };

634 /// HasSideEffects - This routine returns true for all those expressions
635 /// which have any effect other than producing a value. Example is a function
636 /// call, volatile variable read, or throwing an exception. If
637 /// IncludePossibleEffects is false, this call treats certain expressions with
638 /// potential side effects (such as function call-like expressions,
639 /// instantiation-dependent expressions, or invocations from a macro) as not
640 /// having side effects.
641 bool HasSideEffects(const ASTContext &Ctx,
642 bool IncludePossibleEffects = true) const;

665 /// EvaluateAsInitializer - Evaluate an expression as if it were the
666 /// initializer of the given declaration. Returns true if the initializer
667 /// can be folded to a constant, and produces any relevant notes. In C++11,
668 /// notes will be produced if the expression is not a constant expression.

1069/// A reference to a declared variable, function, enum, etc.
1070/// [C99 6.5.1p2]
1071///
1072/// This encodes all the information about how a declaration is referenced
1073/// within an expression.
1074///
1075/// There are several optional constructs attached to DeclRefExprs only when
1076/// they apply in order to conserve memory. These are laid out past the end of
1077/// the object, and flags in the DeclRefExprBitfield track whether they exist:
1078///
1079/// DeclRefExprBits.HasQualifier:
1080/// Specifies when this declaration reference expression has a C++
1081/// nested-name-specifier.
1082/// DeclRefExprBits.HasFoundDecl:
1083/// Specifies when this declaration reference expression has a record of
1084/// a NamedDecl (different from the referenced ValueDecl) which was found
1085/// during name lookup and/or overload resolution.
1086/// DeclRefExprBits.HasTemplateKWAndArgsInfo:
1087/// Specifies when this declaration reference expression has an explicit
1088/// C++ template keyword and/or template argument list.
1089/// DeclRefExprBits.RefersToEnclosingVariableOrCapture
1090/// Specifies when this declaration reference expression (validly)
1091/// refers to an enclosed local or a captured variable.
1092class DeclRefExpr final
1093 : public Expr,
1094 private llvm::TrailingObjects<DeclRefExpr, NestedNameSpecifierLoc,
1095 NamedDecl *, ASTTemplateKWAndArgsInfo,
1096 TemplateArgumentLoc> {
1097 friend class ASTStmtReader;
1098 friend class ASTStmtWriter;
1099 friend TrailingObjects;
1100
1101 /// The declaration that we are referencing.
1102 ValueDecl *D;
1103
1104 /// Provides source/type location info for the declaration name
1105 /// embedded in D.
1106 DeclarationNameLoc DNLoc;
1107
1108 size_t numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<NestedNameSpecifierLoc>) const {
1109 return hasQualifier();
1110 }
1111
1112 size_t numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<NamedDecl *>) const {
1113 return hasFoundDecl();
1114 }
1115
1116 size_t numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<ASTTemplateKWAndArgsInfo>) const {
1117 return hasTemplateKWAndArgsInfo();
1118 }
1119
1120 /// Test whether there is a distinct FoundDecl attached to the end of
1121 /// this DRE.
1122 bool hasFoundDecl() const { return DeclRefExprBits.HasFoundDecl; }
1123
1124 DeclRefExpr(const ASTContext &Ctx, NestedNameSpecifierLoc QualifierLoc,
1125 SourceLocation TemplateKWLoc, ValueDecl *D,
1126 bool RefersToEnlosingVariableOrCapture,
1127 const DeclarationNameInfo &NameInfo, NamedDecl *FoundD,
1128 const TemplateArgumentListInfo *TemplateArgs, QualType T,
1129 ExprValueKind VK, NonOdrUseReason NOUR);

1317/// leaking memory.
1318///
1319/// For large floats/integers, APFloat/APInt will allocate memory from the heap
1320/// to represent these numbers. Unfortunately, when we use a BumpPtrAllocator
1321/// to allocate IntegerLiteral/FloatingLiteral nodes the memory associated with
1322/// the APFloat/APInt values will never get freed. APNumericStorage uses
1323/// ASTContext's allocator for memory allocation.
1324class APNumericStorage {
1325 union {
1326 uint64_t VAL; ///< Used to store the <= 64 bits integer value.
1327 uint64_t *pVal; ///< Used to store the >64 bits integer value.
1328 };
1329 unsigned BitWidth;
1330
1331 bool hasAllocation() const { return llvm::APInt::getNumWords(BitWidth) > 1; }
1332
1333 APNumericStorage(const APNumericStorage &) = delete;
1334 void operator=(const APNumericStorage &) = delete;
1335
1336protected:
1337 APNumericStorage() : VAL(0), BitWidth(0) { }
1338
1339 llvm::APInt getIntValue() const {
1340 unsigned NumWords = llvm::APInt::getNumWords(BitWidth);
1341 if (NumWords > 1)
1342 return llvm::APInt(BitWidth, NumWords, pVal);
1343 else
1344 return llvm::APInt(BitWidth, VAL);
1345 }
1346 void setIntValue(const ASTContext &C, const llvm::APInt &Val);
1347};
1348
1349class APIntStorage : private APNumericStorage {
1350public:
1351 llvm::APInt getValue() const { return getIntValue(); }
1352 void setValue(const ASTContext &C, const llvm::APInt &Val) {
1353 setIntValue(C, Val);
1354 }
1355};

1361 }
1362 void setValue(const ASTContext &C, const llvm::APFloat &Val) {

1608/// StringLiteral - This represents a string literal expression, e.g. "foo"
1609/// or L"bar" (wide strings). The actual string data can be obtained with
1610/// getBytes() and is NOT null-terminated. The length of the string data is
1611/// determined by calling getByteLength().
1612///
1613/// The C type for a string is always a ConstantArrayType. In C++, the char
1614/// type is const qualified, in C it is not.
1615///
1616/// Note that strings in C can be formed by concatenation of multiple string
1617/// literal pptokens in translation phase #6. This keeps track of the locations
1618/// of each of these pieces.
1619///
1620/// Strings in C can also be truncated and extended by assigning into arrays,
1621/// e.g. with constructs like:
1622/// char X[2] = "foobar";
1623/// In this case, getByteLength() will return 6, but the string literal will
1624/// have type "char[2]".
1625class StringLiteral final
1626 : public Expr,
1627 private llvm::TrailingObjects<StringLiteral, unsigned, SourceLocation,
1628 char> {
1629 friend class ASTStmtReader;
1630 friend TrailingObjects;
1631
1632 /// StringLiteral is followed by several trailing objects. They are in order:
1633 ///
1634 /// * A single unsigned storing the length in characters of this string. The
1635 /// length in bytes is this length times the width of a single character.
1636 /// Always present and stored as a trailing objects because storing it in
1637 /// StringLiteral would increase the size of StringLiteral by sizeof(void *)
1638 /// due to alignment requirements. If you add some data to StringLiteral,
1639 /// consider moving it inside StringLiteral.
1640 ///
1641 /// * An array of getNumConcatenated() SourceLocation, one for each of the
1642 /// token this string is made of.
1643 ///
1644 /// * An array of getByteLength() char used to store the string data.
1645
1646public:
1647 enum StringKind { Ascii, Wide, UTF8, UTF16, UTF32 };
1648
1649private:
1650 unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<unsigned>) const { return 1; }
1651 unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<SourceLocation>) const {
1652 return getNumConcatenated();
1653 }
1654
1655 unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<char>) const {
1656 return getByteLength();
1657 }
1658
1659 char *getStrDataAsChar() { return getTrailingObjects<char>(); }
1660 const char *getStrDataAsChar() const { return getTrailingObjects<char>(); }
1661
1662 const uint16_t *getStrDataAsUInt16() const {
1663 return reinterpret_cast<const uint16_t *>(getTrailingObjects<char>());
1664 }
1665
1666 const uint32_t *getStrDataAsUInt32() const {
1667 return reinterpret_cast<const uint32_t *>(getTrailingObjects<char>());
1668 }
1669
1670 /// Build a string literal.
1671 StringLiteral(const ASTContext &Ctx, StringRef Str, StringKind Kind,
1672 bool Pascal, QualType Ty, const SourceLocation *Loc,
1673 unsigned NumConcatenated);
1674
1675 /// Build an empty string literal.
1676 StringLiteral(EmptyShell Empty, unsigned NumConcatenated, unsigned Length,
1677 unsigned CharByteWidth);
1678
1679 /// Map a target and string kind to the appropriate character width.
1680 static unsigned mapCharByteWidth(TargetInfo const &Target, StringKind SK);
1681
1682 /// Set one of the string literal token.
1683 void setStrTokenLoc(unsigned TokNum, SourceLocation L) {
1684 assert(TokNum < getNumConcatenated() && "Invalid tok number");
1685 getTrailingObjects<SourceLocation>()[TokNum] = L;
1686 }
1687
1688public:
1689 /// This is the "fully general" constructor that allows representation of
1690 /// strings formed from multiple concatenated tokens.
1691 static StringLiteral *Create(const ASTContext &Ctx, StringRef Str,
1692 StringKind Kind, bool Pascal, QualType Ty,
1693 const SourceLocation *Loc,
1694 unsigned NumConcatenated);
1695
1696 /// Simple constructor for string literals made from one token.
1697 static StringLiteral *Create(const ASTContext &Ctx, StringRef Str,
1698 StringKind Kind, bool Pascal, QualType Ty,
1699 SourceLocation Loc) {
1700 return Create(Ctx, Str, Kind, Pascal, Ty, &Loc, 1);
1701 }
1702
1703 /// Construct an empty string literal.
1704 static StringLiteral *CreateEmpty(const ASTContext &Ctx,
1705 unsigned NumConcatenated, unsigned Length,
1706 unsigned CharByteWidth);
1707
1708 StringRef getString() const {
1709 assert(getCharByteWidth() == 1 &&
1710 "This function is used in places that assume strings use char");
1711 return StringRef(getStrDataAsChar(), getByteLength());
1712 }
1713
1714 /// Allow access to clients that need the byte representation, such as
1715 /// ASTWriterStmt::VisitStringLiteral().
1716 StringRef getBytes() const {
1717 // FIXME: StringRef may not be the right type to use as a result for this.
1718 return StringRef(getStrDataAsChar(), getByteLength());
1719 }
1720
1721 void outputString(raw_ostream &OS) const;
1722
1723 uint32_t getCodeUnit(size_t i) const {
1724 assert(i < getLength() && "out of bounds access");
1725 switch (getCharByteWidth()) {
1726 case 1:
1727 return static_cast<unsigned char>(getStrDataAsChar()[i]);
1728 case 2:
1729 return getStrDataAsUInt16()[i];
1730 case 4:
1731 return getStrDataAsUInt32()[i];
1732 }
1733 llvm_unreachable("Unsupported character width!");
1734 }
1735
1736 unsigned getByteLength() const { return getCharByteWidth() * getLength(); }
1737 unsigned getLength() const { return *getTrailingObjects<unsigned>(); }
1738 unsigned getCharByteWidth() const { return StringLiteralBits.CharByteWidth; }
1739
1740 StringKind getKind() const {
1741 return static_cast<StringKind>(StringLiteralBits.Kind);
1742 }
1743
1744 bool isAscii() const { return getKind() == Ascii; }
1745 bool isWide() const { return getKind() == Wide; }
1746 bool isUTF8() const { return getKind() == UTF8; }
1747 bool isUTF16() const { return getKind() == UTF16; }
1748 bool isUTF32() const { return getKind() == UTF32; }
1749 bool isPascal() const { return StringLiteralBits.IsPascal; }
1750
1751 bool containsNonAscii() const {
1752 for (auto c : getString())
1753 if (!isASCII(c))
1754 return true;
1755 return false;
1756 }
1757
1758 bool containsNonAsciiOrNull() const {
1759 for (auto c : getString())
1760 if (!isASCII(c) || !c)
1761 return true;
1762 return false;
1763 }
1764
1765 /// getNumConcatenated - Get the number of string literal tokens that were
1766 /// concatenated in translation phase #6 to form this string literal.
1767 unsigned getNumConcatenated() const {
1768 return StringLiteralBits.NumConcatenated;
1769 }
1770
1771 /// Get one of the string literal token.
1772 SourceLocation getStrTokenLoc(unsigned TokNum) const {
1773 assert(TokNum < getNumConcatenated() && "Invalid tok number");
1774 return getTrailingObjects<SourceLocation>()[TokNum];
1775 }
1776
1777 /// getLocationOfByte - Return a source location that points to the specified
1778 /// byte of this string literal.
1779 ///
1780 /// Strings are amazingly complex. They can be formed from multiple tokens
1781 /// and can have escape sequences in them in addition to the usual trigraph
1782 /// and escaped newline business. This routine handles this complexity.
1783 ///
1784 SourceLocation
1785 getLocationOfByte(unsigned ByteNo, const SourceManager &SM,
1786 const LangOptions &Features, const TargetInfo &Target,
1787 unsigned *StartToken = nullptr,
1788 unsigned *StartTokenByteOffset = nullptr) const;
1789
1790 typedef const SourceLocation *tokloc_iterator;
1791
1792 tokloc_iterator tokloc_begin() const {
1793 return getTrailingObjects<SourceLocation>();
1794 }
1795
1796 tokloc_iterator tokloc_end() const {
1797 return getTrailingObjects<SourceLocation>() + getNumConcatenated();
1798 }
1799
1800 SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return *tokloc_begin(); }
1801 SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return *(tokloc_end() - 1); }
1802
1803 static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
1804 return T->getStmtClass() == StringLiteralClass;
1805 }
1806
1807 // Iterators
1808 child_range children() {
1809 return child_range(child_iterator(), child_iterator());
1810 }
1811 const_child_range children() const {
1812 return const_child_range(const_child_iterator(), const_child_iterator());
1813 }
1814};

1950/// UnaryOperator - This represents the unary-expression's (except sizeof and

2074/// Helper class for OffsetOfExpr.
2075
2076// __builtin_offsetof(type, identifier(.identifier|[expr])*)
2077class OffsetOfNode {
2078public:
2079 /// The kind of offsetof node we have.
2080 enum Kind {
2081 /// An index into an array.
2082 Array = 0x00,
2083 /// A field.
2084 Field = 0x01,
2085 /// A field in a dependent type, known only by its name.
2086 Identifier = 0x02,
2087 /// An implicit indirection through a C++ base class, when the
2088 /// field found is in a base class.
2089 Base = 0x03
2090 };
2091
2092private:
2093 enum { MaskBits = 2, Mask = 0x03 };
2094
2095 /// The source range that covers this part of the designator.
2096 SourceRange Range;
2097
2098 /// The data describing the designator, which comes in three
2099 /// different forms, depending on the lower two bits.
2100 /// - An unsigned index into the array of Expr*'s stored after this node
2101 /// in memory, for [constant-expression] designators.
2102 /// - A FieldDecl*, for references to a known field.
2103 /// - An IdentifierInfo*, for references to a field with a given name
2104 /// when the class type is dependent.
2105 /// - A CXXBaseSpecifier*, for references that look at a field in a
2106 /// base class.
2107 uintptr_t Data;
2108
2109public:
2110 /// Create an offsetof node that refers to an array element.
2111 OffsetOfNode(SourceLocation LBracketLoc, unsigned Index,
2112 SourceLocation RBracketLoc)
2113 : Range(LBracketLoc, RBracketLoc), Data((Index << 2) | Array) {}
2114
2115 /// Create an offsetof node that refers to a field.
2116 OffsetOfNode(SourceLocation DotLoc, FieldDecl *Field, SourceLocation NameLoc)
2117 : Range(DotLoc.isValid() ? DotLoc : NameLoc, NameLoc),
2118 Data(reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(Field) | OffsetOfNode::Field) {}
2119
2120 /// Create an offsetof node that refers to an identifier.
2121 OffsetOfNode(SourceLocation DotLoc, IdentifierInfo *Name,
2122 SourceLocation NameLoc)
2123 : Range(DotLoc.isValid() ? DotLoc : NameLoc, NameLoc),
2124 Data(reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(Name) | Identifier) {}
2125
2126 /// Create an offsetof node that refers into a C++ base class.
2127 explicit OffsetOfNode(const CXXBaseSpecifier *Base)
2128 : Range(), Data(reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(Base) | OffsetOfNode::Base) {}
2129
2130 /// Determine what kind of offsetof node this is.
2131 Kind getKind() const { return static_cast<Kind>(Data & Mask); }
2132
2133 /// For an array element node, returns the index into the array
2134 /// of expressions.
2135 unsigned getArrayExprIndex() const {
2136 assert(getKind() == Array);
2137 return Data >> 2;
2138 }
2139
2140 /// For a field offsetof node, returns the field.
2141 FieldDecl *getField() const {
2142 assert(getKind() == Field);
2143 return reinterpret_cast<FieldDecl *>(Data & ~(uintptr_t)Mask);
2144 }
2145
2146 /// For a field or identifier offsetof node, returns the name of
2147 /// the field.
2148 IdentifierInfo *getFieldName() const;
2149
2150 /// For a base class node, returns the base specifier.
2151 CXXBaseSpecifier *getBase() const {
2152 assert(getKind() == Base);
2153 return reinterpret_cast<CXXBaseSpecifier *>(Data & ~(uintptr_t)Mask);
2154 }
2155
2156 /// Retrieve the source range that covers this offsetof node.
2157 ///
2158 /// For an array element node, the source range contains the locations of
2159 /// the square brackets. For a field or identifier node, the source range
2160 /// contains the location of the period (if there is one) and the
2161 /// identifier.
2162 SourceRange getSourceRange() const LLVM_READONLY { return Range; }
2163 SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return Range.getBegin(); }
2164 SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return Range.getEnd(); }
2165};

2454/// CallExpr - Represents a function call (C99 6.5.2.2, C++ [expr.call]).
2455/// CallExpr itself represents a normal function call, e.g., "f(x, 2)",
2456/// while its subclasses may represent alternative syntax that (semantically)
2457/// results in a function call. For example, CXXOperatorCallExpr is
2458/// a subclass for overloaded operator calls that use operator syntax, e.g.,
2459/// "str1 + str2" to resolve to a function call.
2460class CallExpr : public Expr {
2461 enum { FN = 0, PREARGS_START = 1 };
2462
2463 /// The number of arguments in the call expression.
2464 unsigned NumArgs;
2465
2466 /// The location of the right parenthese. This has a different meaning for
2467 /// the derived classes of CallExpr.
2468 SourceLocation RParenLoc;
2469
2470 void updateDependenciesFromArg(Expr *Arg);
2471
2472 // CallExpr store some data in trailing objects. However since CallExpr
2473 // is used a base of other expression classes we cannot use
2474 // llvm::TrailingObjects. Instead we manually perform the pointer arithmetic
2475 // and casts.
2476 //
2477 // The trailing objects are in order:
2478 //
2479 // * A single "Stmt *" for the callee expression.
2480 //
2481 // * An array of getNumPreArgs() "Stmt *" for the pre-argument expressions.
2482 //
2483 // * An array of getNumArgs() "Stmt *" for the argument expressions.
2484 //
2485 // Note that we store the offset in bytes from the this pointer to the start
2486 // of the trailing objects. It would be perfectly possible to compute it
2487 // based on the dynamic kind of the CallExpr. However 1.) we have plenty of
2488 // space in the bit-fields of Stmt. 2.) It was benchmarked to be faster to
2489 // compute this once and then load the offset from the bit-fields of Stmt,
2490 // instead of re-computing the offset each time the trailing objects are
2491 // accessed.
2492
2493 /// Return a pointer to the start of the trailing array of "Stmt *".
2494 Stmt **getTrailingStmts() {
2495 return reinterpret_cast<Stmt **>(reinterpret_cast<char *>(this) +
2496 CallExprBits.OffsetToTrailingObjects);
2497 }
2498 Stmt *const *getTrailingStmts() const {
2499 return const_cast<CallExpr *>(this)->getTrailingStmts();
2500 }
2501
2502 /// Map a statement class to the appropriate offset in bytes from the
2503 /// this pointer to the trailing objects.
2504 static unsigned offsetToTrailingObjects(StmtClass SC);
2505
2506public:
2507 enum class ADLCallKind : bool { NotADL, UsesADL };
2508 static constexpr ADLCallKind NotADL = ADLCallKind::NotADL;
2509 static constexpr ADLCallKind UsesADL = ADLCallKind::UsesADL;
2510
2511protected:
2512 /// Build a call expression, assuming that appropriate storage has been
2513 /// allocated for the trailing objects.
2514 CallExpr(StmtClass SC, Expr *Fn, ArrayRef<Expr *> PreArgs,
2515 ArrayRef<Expr *> Args, QualType Ty, ExprValueKind VK,
2516 SourceLocation RParenLoc, unsigned MinNumArgs, ADLCallKind UsesADL);
2517
2518 /// Build an empty call expression, for deserialization.
2519 CallExpr(StmtClass SC, unsigned NumPreArgs, unsigned NumArgs,
2520 EmptyShell Empty);
2521
2522 /// Return the size in bytes needed for the trailing objects.
2523 /// Used by the derived classes to allocate the right amount of storage.
2524 static unsigned sizeOfTrailingObjects(unsigned NumPreArgs, unsigned NumArgs) {
2525 return (1 + NumPreArgs + NumArgs) * sizeof(Stmt *);
2526 }
2527
2528 Stmt *getPreArg(unsigned I) {
2529 assert(I < getNumPreArgs() && "Prearg access out of range!");
2530 return getTrailingStmts()[PREARGS_START + I];
2531 }
2532 const Stmt *getPreArg(unsigned I) const {
2533 assert(I < getNumPreArgs() && "Prearg access out of range!");
2534 return getTrailingStmts()[PREARGS_START + I];
2535 }
2536 void setPreArg(unsigned I, Stmt *PreArg) {
2537 assert(I < getNumPreArgs() && "Prearg access out of range!");
2538 getTrailingStmts()[PREARGS_START + I] = PreArg;
2539 }
2540
2541 unsigned getNumPreArgs() const { return CallExprBits.NumPreArgs; }
2542
2543public:
2544 /// Create a call expression. Fn is the callee expression, Args is the
2545 /// argument array, Ty is the type of the call expression (which is *not*
2546 /// the return type in general), VK is the value kind of the call expression
2547 /// (lvalue, rvalue, ...), and RParenLoc is the location of the right
2548 /// parenthese in the call expression. MinNumArgs specifies the minimum
2549 /// number of arguments. The actual number of arguments will be the greater
2550 /// of Args.size() and MinNumArgs. This is used in a few places to allocate
2551 /// enough storage for the default arguments. UsesADL specifies whether the
2552 /// callee was found through argument-dependent lookup.
2553 ///
2554 /// Note that you can use CreateTemporary if you need a temporary call
2555 /// expression on the stack.
2556 static CallExpr *Create(const ASTContext &Ctx, Expr *Fn,
2557 ArrayRef<Expr *> Args, QualType Ty, ExprValueKind VK,
2558 SourceLocation RParenLoc, unsigned MinNumArgs = 0,
2559 ADLCallKind UsesADL = NotADL);
2560
2561 /// Create a temporary call expression with no arguments in the memory
2562 /// pointed to by Mem. Mem must points to at least sizeof(CallExpr)
2563 /// + sizeof(Stmt *) bytes of storage, aligned to alignof(CallExpr):
2564 ///
2565 /// \code{.cpp}
2566 /// llvm::AlignedCharArray<alignof(CallExpr),
2567 /// sizeof(CallExpr) + sizeof(Stmt *)> Buffer;
2568 /// CallExpr *TheCall = CallExpr::CreateTemporary(Buffer.buffer, etc);
2569 /// \endcode
2570 static CallExpr *CreateTemporary(void *Mem, Expr *Fn, QualType Ty,
2571 ExprValueKind VK, SourceLocation RParenLoc,
2572 ADLCallKind UsesADL = NotADL);
2573
2574 /// Create an empty call expression, for deserialization.
2575 static CallExpr *CreateEmpty(const ASTContext &Ctx, unsigned NumArgs,
2576 EmptyShell Empty);
2577
2578 Expr *getCallee() { return cast<Expr>(getTrailingStmts()[FN]); }
2579 const Expr *getCallee() const { return cast<Expr>(getTrailingStmts()[FN]); }
2580 void setCallee(Expr *F) { getTrailingStmts()[FN] = F; }
2581
2582 ADLCallKind getADLCallKind() const {
2583 return static_cast<ADLCallKind>(CallExprBits.UsesADL);
2584 }

3169/// ImplicitCastExpr - Allows us to explicitly represent implicit type
3170/// conversions, which have no direct representation in the original
3171/// source code. For example: converting T[]->T*, void f()->void
3172/// (*f)(), float->double, short->int, etc.
3173///
3174/// In C, implicit casts always produce rvalues. However, in C++, an
3175/// implicit cast whose result is being bound to a reference will be
3176/// an lvalue or xvalue. For example:
3177///
3178/// @code
3179/// class Base { };
3180/// class Derived : public Base { };
3181/// Derived &&ref();
3182/// void f(Derived d) {
3183/// Base& b = d; // initializer is an ImplicitCastExpr
3184/// // to an lvalue of type Base
3185/// Base&& r = ref(); // initializer is an ImplicitCastExpr
3186/// // to an xvalue of type Base
3187/// }
3188/// @endcode
3189class ImplicitCastExpr final
3190 : public CastExpr,
3191 private llvm::TrailingObjects<ImplicitCastExpr, CXXBaseSpecifier *> {
3192
3193 ImplicitCastExpr(QualType ty, CastKind kind, Expr *op,
3194 unsigned BasePathLength, ExprValueKind VK)
3195 : CastExpr(ImplicitCastExprClass, ty, VK, kind, op, BasePathLength) { }
3196
3197 /// Construct an empty implicit cast.
3198 explicit ImplicitCastExpr(EmptyShell Shell, unsigned PathSize)
3199 : CastExpr(ImplicitCastExprClass, Shell, PathSize) { }
3200

3202 enum OnStack_t { OnStack };

3204 ExprValueKind VK)
3205 : CastExpr(ImplicitCastExprClass, ty, VK, kind, op, 0) {
3206 }

3236/// ExplicitCastExpr - An explicit cast written in the source
3237/// code.
3238///
3239/// This class is effectively an abstract class, because it provides
3240/// the basic representation of an explicitly-written cast without
3241/// specifying which kind of cast (C cast, functional cast, static
3242/// cast, etc.) was written; specific derived classes represent the
3243/// particular style of cast and its location information.
3244///
3245/// Unlike implicit casts, explicit cast nodes have two different
3246/// types: the type that was written into the source code, and the
3247/// actual type of the expression as determined by semantic
3248/// analysis. These types may differ slightly. For example, in C++ one
3249/// can cast to a reference type, which indicates that the resulting
3250/// expression will be an lvalue or xvalue. The reference type, however,
3251/// will not be used as the type of the expression.
3252class ExplicitCastExpr : public CastExpr {
3253 /// TInfo - Source type info for the (written) type
3254 /// this expression is casting to.
3255 TypeSourceInfo *TInfo;
3256
3257protected:
3258 ExplicitCastExpr(StmtClass SC, QualType exprTy, ExprValueKind VK,
3259 CastKind kind, Expr *op, unsigned PathSize,
3260 TypeSourceInfo *writtenTy)
3261 : CastExpr(SC, exprTy, VK, kind, op, PathSize), TInfo(writtenTy) {}
3262
3263 /// Construct an empty explicit cast.
3264 ExplicitCastExpr(StmtClass SC, EmptyShell Shell, unsigned PathSize)
3265 : CastExpr(SC, Shell, PathSize) { }
3266
3267public:
3268 /// getTypeInfoAsWritten - Returns the type source info for the type
3269 /// that this expression is casting to.
3270 TypeSourceInfo *getTypeInfoAsWritten() const { return TInfo; }
3271 void setTypeInfoAsWritten(TypeSourceInfo *writtenTy) { TInfo = writtenTy; }
3272
3273 /// getTypeAsWritten - Returns the type that this expression is
3274 /// casting to, as written in the source code.
3275 QualType getTypeAsWritten() const { return TInfo->getType(); }
3276
3277 static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
3278 return T->getStmtClass() >= firstExplicitCastExprConstant &&
3279 T->getStmtClass() <= lastExplicitCastExprConstant;
3280 }

3331/// A builtin binary operation expression such as "x + y" or "x <= y".
3332///
3333/// This expression node kind describes a builtin binary operation,
3334/// such as "x + y" for integer values "x" and "y". The operands will
3335/// already have been converted to appropriate types (e.g., by
3336/// performing promotions or conversions).
3337///
3338/// In C++, where operators may be overloaded, a different kind of
3339/// expression node (CXXOperatorCallExpr) is used to express the
3340/// invocation of an overloaded operator with operator syntax. Within
3341/// a C++ template, whether BinaryOperator or CXXOperatorCallExpr is
3342/// used to store an expression "x + y" depends on the subexpressions
3343/// for x and y. If neither x or y is type-dependent, and the "+"
3344/// operator resolves to a built-in operation, BinaryOperator will be
3345/// used to express the computation (x and y may still be
3346/// value-dependent). If either x or y is type-dependent, or if the
3347/// "+" resolves to an overloaded operator, CXXOperatorCallExpr will
3348/// be used to express the computation.
3349class BinaryOperator : public Expr {
3350 enum { LHS, RHS, END_EXPR };
3351 Stmt *SubExprs[END_EXPR];
3352
3353public:
3354 typedef BinaryOperatorKind Opcode;
3355
3356 BinaryOperator(Expr *lhs, Expr *rhs, Opcode opc, QualType ResTy,
3357 ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK,
3358 SourceLocation opLoc, FPOptions FPFeatures)
3359 : Expr(BinaryOperatorClass, ResTy, VK, OK,
3360 lhs->isTypeDependent() || rhs->isTypeDependent(),
3361 lhs->isValueDependent() || rhs->isValueDependent(),
3362 (lhs->isInstantiationDependent() ||
3363 rhs->isInstantiationDependent()),
3364 (lhs->containsUnexpandedParameterPack() ||
3365 rhs->containsUnexpandedParameterPack())) {
3366 BinaryOperatorBits.Opc = opc;
3367 BinaryOperatorBits.FPFeatures = FPFeatures.getInt();
3368 BinaryOperatorBits.OpLoc = opLoc;
3369 SubExprs[LHS] = lhs;
3370 SubExprs[RHS] = rhs;
3371 assert(!isCompoundAssignmentOp() &&
3372 "Use CompoundAssignOperator for compound assignments");
3373 }
3374
3375 /// Construct an empty binary operator.
3376 explicit BinaryOperator(EmptyShell Empty) : Expr(BinaryOperatorClass, Empty) {
3377 BinaryOperatorBits.Opc = BO_Comma;
3378 }
3379
3380 SourceLocation getExprLoc() const { return getOperatorLoc(); }
3381 SourceLocation getOperatorLoc() const { return BinaryOperatorBits.OpLoc; }
3382 void setOperatorLoc(SourceLocation L) { BinaryOperatorBits.OpLoc = L; }
3383
3384 Opcode getOpcode() const {
3385 return static_cast<Opcode>(BinaryOperatorBits.Opc);
3386 }
3387 void setOpcode(Opcode Opc) { BinaryOperatorBits.Opc = Opc; }
3388
3389 Expr *getLHS() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[LHS]); }
3390 void setLHS(Expr *E) { SubExprs[LHS] = E; }
3391 Expr *getRHS() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[RHS]); }
3392 void setRHS(Expr *E) { SubExprs[RHS] = E; }
3393
3394 SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
3395 return getLHS()->getBeginLoc();
3396 }
3397 SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
3398 return getRHS()->getEndLoc();
3399 }

3450 case BO_GT: return BO_LE;
3451 case BO_LE: return BO_GT;

3462 case BO_LT: return BO_GT;
3463 case BO_GT: return BO_LT;
3464 case BO_LE: return BO_GE;
3465 case BO_GE: return BO_LE;
3466 case BO_EQ:
3467 case BO_NE:
3468 return Opc;
3469 }

4270/// Describes an C or C++ initializer list.
4271///
4272/// InitListExpr describes an initializer list, which can be used to
4273/// initialize objects of different types, including
4274/// struct/class/union types, arrays, and vectors. For example:
4275///
4276/// @code
4277/// struct foo x = { 1, { 2, 3 } };
4278/// @endcode
4279///
4280/// Prior to semantic analysis, an initializer list will represent the
4281/// initializer list as written by the user, but will have the
4282/// placeholder type "void". This initializer list is called the
4283/// syntactic form of the initializer, and may contain C99 designated
4284/// initializers (represented as DesignatedInitExprs), initializations
4285/// of subobject members without explicit braces, and so on. Clients
4286/// interested in the original syntax of the initializer list should
4287/// use the syntactic form of the initializer list.
4288///
4289/// After semantic analysis, the initializer list will represent the
4290/// semantic form of the initializer, where the initializations of all
4291/// subobjects are made explicit with nested InitListExpr nodes and
4292/// C99 designators have been eliminated by placing the designated
4293/// initializations into the subobject they initialize. Additionally,
4294/// any "holes" in the initialization, where no initializer has been
4295/// specified for a particular subobject, will be replaced with
4296/// implicitly-generated ImplicitValueInitExpr expressions that
4297/// value-initialize the subobjects. Note, however, that the
4298/// initializer lists may still have fewer initializers than there are
4299/// elements to initialize within the object.
4300///
4301/// After semantic analysis has completed, given an initializer list,
4302/// method isSemanticForm() returns true if and only if this is the
4303/// semantic form of the initializer list (note: the same AST node
4304/// may at the same time be the syntactic form).
4305/// Given the semantic form of the initializer list, one can retrieve
4306/// the syntactic form of that initializer list (when different)
4307/// using method getSyntacticForm(); the method returns null if applied
4308/// to a initializer list which is already in syntactic form.
4309/// Similarly, given the syntactic form (i.e., an initializer list such
4310/// that isSemanticForm() returns false), one can retrieve the semantic
4311/// form using method getSemanticForm().
4312/// Since many initializer lists have the same syntactic and semantic forms,
4313/// getSyntacticForm() may return NULL, indicating that the current
4314/// semantic initializer list also serves as its syntactic form.
4315class InitListExpr : public Expr {
4316 // FIXME: Eliminate this vector in favor of ASTContext allocation
4317 typedef ASTVector<Stmt *> InitExprsTy;
4318 InitExprsTy InitExprs;
4319 SourceLocation LBraceLoc, RBraceLoc;
4320
4321 /// The alternative form of the initializer list (if it exists).
4322 /// The int part of the pair stores whether this initializer list is
4323 /// in semantic form. If not null, the pointer points to:
4324 /// - the syntactic form, if this is in semantic form;
4325 /// - the semantic form, if this is in syntactic form.
4326 llvm::PointerIntPair<InitListExpr *, 1, bool> AltForm;
4327
4328 /// Either:
4329 /// If this initializer list initializes an array with more elements than
4330 /// there are initializers in the list, specifies an expression to be used
4331 /// for value initialization of the rest of the elements.
4332 /// Or
4333 /// If this initializer list initializes a union, specifies which
4334 /// field within the union will be initialized.
4335 llvm::PointerUnion<Expr *, FieldDecl *> ArrayFillerOrUnionFieldInit;
4336
4337public:
4338 InitListExpr(const ASTContext &C, SourceLocation lbraceloc,
4339 ArrayRef<Expr*> initExprs, SourceLocation rbraceloc);
4340
4341 /// Build an empty initializer list.
4342 explicit InitListExpr(EmptyShell Empty)
4343 : Expr(InitListExprClass, Empty), AltForm(nullptr, true) { }
4344
4345 unsigned getNumInits() const { return InitExprs.size(); }
4346
4347 /// Retrieve the set of initializers.
4348 Expr **getInits() { return reinterpret_cast<Expr **>(InitExprs.data()); }
4349
4350 /// Retrieve the set of initializers.
4351 Expr * const *getInits() const {
4352 return reinterpret_cast<Expr * const *>(InitExprs.data());
4353 }
4354
4355 ArrayRef<Expr *> inits() {
4356 return llvm::makeArrayRef(getInits(), getNumInits());
4357 }
4358
4359 ArrayRef<Expr *> inits() const {
4360 return llvm::makeArrayRef(getInits(), getNumInits());
4361 }
4362
4363 const Expr *getInit(unsigned Init) const {
4364 assert(Init < getNumInits() && "Initializer access out of range!");
4365 return cast_or_null<Expr>(InitExprs[Init]);
4366 }
4367
4368 Expr *getInit(unsigned Init) {
4369 assert(Init < getNumInits() && "Initializer access out of range!");
4370 return cast_or_null<Expr>(InitExprs[Init]);
4371 }
4372
4373 void setInit(unsigned Init, Expr *expr) {
4374 assert(Init < getNumInits() && "Initializer access out of range!");
4375 InitExprs[Init] = expr;
4376
4377 if (expr) {
4378 ExprBits.TypeDependent |= expr->isTypeDependent();
4379 ExprBits.ValueDependent |= expr->isValueDependent();
4380 ExprBits.InstantiationDependent |= expr->isInstantiationDependent();
4381 ExprBits.ContainsUnexpandedParameterPack |=
4382 expr->containsUnexpandedParameterPack();
4383 }
4384 }
4385
4386 /// Reserve space for some number of initializers.
4387 void reserveInits(const ASTContext &C, unsigned NumInits);
4388
4389 /// Specify the number of initializers
4390 ///
4391 /// If there are more than @p NumInits initializers, the remaining
4392 /// initializers will be destroyed. If there are fewer than @p

4529/// Represents a C99 designated initializer expression.
4530///
4531/// A designated initializer expression (C99 6.7.8) contains one or
4532/// more designators (which can be field designators, array
4533/// designators, or GNU array-range designators) followed by an
4534/// expression that initializes the field or element(s) that the
4535/// designators refer to. For example, given:
4536///
4537/// @code
4538/// struct point {
4539/// double x;
4540/// double y;
4541/// };
4542/// struct point ptarray[10] = { [2].y = 1.0, [2].x = 2.0, [0].x = 1.0 };
4543/// @endcode
4544///
4545/// The InitListExpr contains three DesignatedInitExprs, the first of
4546/// which covers @c [2].y=1.0. This DesignatedInitExpr will have two
4547/// designators, one array designator for @c [2] followed by one field
4548/// designator for @c .y. The initialization expression will be 1.0.
4549class DesignatedInitExpr final
4550 : public Expr,
4551 private llvm::TrailingObjects<DesignatedInitExpr, Stmt *> {
4552public:
4553 /// Forward declaration of the Designator class.
4554 class Designator;
4555
4556private:
4557 /// The location of the '=' or ':' prior to the actual initializer
4558 /// expression.
4559 SourceLocation EqualOrColonLoc;
4560
4561 /// Whether this designated initializer used the GNU deprecated
4562 /// syntax rather than the C99 '=' syntax.
4563 unsigned GNUSyntax : 1;
4564
4565 /// The number of designators in this initializer expression.
4566 unsigned NumDesignators : 15;
4567
4568 /// The number of subexpressions of this initializer expression,
4569 /// which contains both the initializer and any additional
4570 /// expressions used by array and array-range designators.
4571 unsigned NumSubExprs : 16;
4572
4573 /// The designators in this designated initialization
4574 /// expression.
4575 Designator *Designators;
4576
4577 DesignatedInitExpr(const ASTContext &C, QualType Ty,
4578 llvm::ArrayRef<Designator> Designators,
4579 SourceLocation EqualOrColonLoc, bool GNUSyntax,
4580 ArrayRef<Expr *> IndexExprs, Expr *Init);
4581
4582 explicit DesignatedInitExpr(unsigned NumSubExprs)
4583 : Expr(DesignatedInitExprClass, EmptyShell()),
4584 NumDesignators(0), NumSubExprs(NumSubExprs), Designators(nullptr) { }
4585
4586public:
4587 /// A field designator, e.g., ".x".
4588 struct FieldDesignator {
4589 /// Refers to the field that is being initialized. The low bit
4590 /// of this field determines whether this is actually a pointer
4591 /// to an IdentifierInfo (if 1) or a FieldDecl (if 0). When
4592 /// initially constructed, a field designator will store an
4593 /// IdentifierInfo*. After semantic analysis has resolved that
4594 /// name, the field designator will instead store a FieldDecl*.
4595 uintptr_t NameOrField;
4596
4597 /// The location of the '.' in the designated initializer.
4598 unsigned DotLoc;
4599
4600 /// The location of the field name in the designated initializer.
4601 unsigned FieldLoc;
4602 };
4603
4604 /// An array or GNU array-range designator, e.g., "[9]" or "[10..15]".
4605 struct ArrayOrRangeDesignator {
4606 /// Location of the first index expression within the designated
4607 /// initializer expression's list of subexpressions.
4608 unsigned Index;
4609 /// The location of the '[' starting the array range designator.
4610 unsigned LBracketLoc;
4611 /// The location of the ellipsis separating the start and end
4612 /// indices. Only valid for GNU array-range designators.
4613 unsigned EllipsisLoc;
4614 /// The location of the ']' terminating the array range designator.
4615 unsigned RBracketLoc;
4616 };

4618 /// Represents a single C99 designator.

4917/// Represents a loop initializing the elements of an array.
4918///
4919/// The need to initialize the elements of an array occurs in a number of
4920/// contexts:
4921///
4922/// * in the implicit copy/move constructor for a class with an array member
4923/// * when a lambda-expression captures an array by value
4924/// * when a decomposition declaration decomposes an array
4925///
4926/// There are two subexpressions: a common expression (the source array)
4927/// that is evaluated once up-front, and a per-element initializer that
4928/// runs once for each array element.
4929///
4930/// Within the per-element initializer, the common expression may be referenced
4931/// via an OpaqueValueExpr, and the current index may be obtained via an
4932/// ArrayInitIndexExpr.

4937 : Expr(ArrayInitLoopExprClass, Empty), SubExprs{} {}

4939public:

4941 : Expr(ArrayInitLoopExprClass, T, VK_RValue, OK_Ordinary, false,
4942 CommonInit->isValueDependent() || ElementInit->isValueDependent(),
4943 T->isInstantiationDependentType(),
4944 CommonInit->containsUnexpandedParameterPack() ||
4945 ElementInit->containsUnexpandedParameterPack()),
4946 SubExprs{CommonInit, ElementInit} {}
4947
4948 /// Get the common subexpression shared by all initializations (the source
4949 /// array).
4950 OpaqueValueExpr *getCommonExpr() const {
4951 return cast<OpaqueValueExpr>(SubExprs[0]);
4952 }
4953
4954 /// Get the initializer to use for each array element.
4955 Expr *getSubExpr() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[1]); }
4956
4957 llvm::APInt getArraySize() const {
4958 return cast<ConstantArrayType>(getType()->castAsArrayTypeUnsafe())
4959 ->getSize();
4960 }

4962 static bool classof(const Stmt *S) {
4963 return S->getStmtClass() == ArrayInitLoopExprClass;

4973 child_range children() {
4974 return child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + 2);
4975 }
4976 const_child_range children() const {
4977 return const_child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + 2);

5114/// Represents a C11 generic selection.
5115///
5116/// A generic selection (C11 6.5.1.1) contains an unevaluated controlling
5117/// expression, followed by one or more generic associations. Each generic
5118/// association specifies a type name and an expression, or "default" and an
5119/// expression (in which case it is known as a default generic association).
5120/// The type and value of the generic selection are identical to those of its
5121/// result expression, which is defined as the expression in the generic
5122/// association with a type name that is compatible with the type of the
5123/// controlling expression, or the expression in the default generic association
5124/// if no types are compatible. For example:
5125///
5126/// @code
5127/// _Generic(X, double: 1, float: 2, default: 3)
5128/// @endcode
5129///
5130/// The above expression evaluates to 1 if 1.0 is substituted for X, 2 if 1.0f
5131/// or 3 if "hello".
5132///
5133/// As an extension, generic selections are allowed in C++, where the following
5134/// additional semantics apply:
5135///
5136/// Any generic selection whose controlling expression is type-dependent or
5137/// which names a dependent type in its association list is result-dependent,
5138/// which means that the choice of result expression is dependent.
5139/// Result-dependent generic associations are both type- and value-dependent.
5140class GenericSelectionExpr final
5141 : public Expr,
5142 private llvm::TrailingObjects<GenericSelectionExpr, Stmt *,
5143 TypeSourceInfo *> {
5144 friend class ASTStmtReader;
5145 friend class ASTStmtWriter;
5146 friend TrailingObjects;
5147
5148 /// The number of association expressions and the index of the result
5149 /// expression in the case where the generic selection expression is not
5150 /// result-dependent. The result index is equal to ResultDependentIndex
5151 /// if and only if the generic selection expression is result-dependent.
5152 unsigned NumAssocs, ResultIndex;
5153 enum : unsigned {
5154 ResultDependentIndex = std::numeric_limits<unsigned>::max(),
5155 ControllingIndex = 0,
5156 AssocExprStartIndex = 1
5157 };
5158
5159 /// The location of the "default" and of the right parenthesis.
5160 SourceLocation DefaultLoc, RParenLoc;
5161
5162 // GenericSelectionExpr is followed by several trailing objects.
5163 // They are (in order):
5164 //
5165 // * A single Stmt * for the controlling expression.
5166 // * An array of getNumAssocs() Stmt * for the association expressions.
5167 // * An array of getNumAssocs() TypeSourceInfo *, one for each of the
5168 // association expressions.
5169 unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<Stmt *>) const {
5170 // Add one to account for the controlling expression; the remainder
5171 // are the associated expressions.
5172 return 1 + getNumAssocs();
5173 }
5174
5175 unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<TypeSourceInfo *>) const {
5176 return getNumAssocs();
5177 }

5179 template <bool Const> class AssociationIteratorTy;
5180 /// Bundle together an association expression and its TypeSourceInfo.
5181 /// The Const template parameter is for the const and non-const versions
5182 /// of AssociationTy.
5183 template <bool Const> class AssociationTy {
5184 friend class GenericSelectionExpr;
5185 template <bool OtherConst> friend class AssociationIteratorTy;
5186 using ExprPtrTy =
5187 typename std::conditional<Const, const Expr *, Expr *>::type;
5188 using TSIPtrTy = typename std::conditional<Const, const TypeSourceInfo *,
5189 TypeSourceInfo *>::type;
5190 ExprPtrTy E;
5191 TSIPtrTy TSI;
5192 bool Selected;
5193 AssociationTy(ExprPtrTy E, TSIPtrTy TSI, bool Selected)
5194 : E(E), TSI(TSI), Selected(Selected) {}
5195
5196 public:
5197 ExprPtrTy getAssociationExpr() const { return E; }
5198 TSIPtrTy getTypeSourceInfo() const { return TSI; }
5199 QualType getType() const { return TSI ? TSI->getType() : QualType(); }

5201 AssociationTy *operator->() { return this; }
5202 const AssociationTy *operator->() const { return this; }
5203 }; // class AssociationTy

5205 /// Iterator over const and non-const Association objects. The Association
5206 /// objects are created on the fly when the iterator is dereferenced.
5207 /// This abstract over how exactly the association expressions and the
5208 /// corresponding TypeSourceInfo * are stored.
5209 template <bool Const>
5210 class AssociationIteratorTy
5211 : public llvm::iterator_facade_base<
5212 AssociationIteratorTy<Const>, std::input_iterator_tag,
5213 AssociationTy<Const>, std::ptrdiff_t, AssociationTy<Const>,
5214 AssociationTy<Const>> {
5215 friend class GenericSelectionExpr;
5216 // FIXME: This iterator could conceptually be a random access iterator, and
5217 // it would be nice if we could strengthen the iterator category someday.
5218 // However this iterator does not satisfy two requirements of forward
5219 // iterators:
5220 // a) reference = T& or reference = const T&
5221 // b) If It1 and It2 are both dereferenceable, then It1 == It2 if and only
5222 // if *It1 and *It2 are bound to the same objects.
5223 // An alternative design approach was discussed during review;
5224 // store an Association object inside the iterator, and return a reference
5225 // to it when dereferenced. This idea was discarded beacuse of nasty
5226 // lifetime issues:
5227 // AssociationIterator It = ...;
5228 // const Association &Assoc = *It++; // Oops, Assoc is dangling.
5229 using BaseTy = typename AssociationIteratorTy::iterator_facade_base;
5230 using StmtPtrPtrTy =
5231 typename std::conditional<Const, const Stmt *const *, Stmt **>::type;
5232 using TSIPtrPtrTy =
5233 typename std::conditional<Const, const TypeSourceInfo *const *,
5234 TypeSourceInfo **>::type;
5235 StmtPtrPtrTy E; // = nullptr; FIXME: Once support for gcc 4.8 is dropped.
5236 TSIPtrPtrTy TSI; // Kept in sync with E.
5237 unsigned Offset = 0, SelectedOffset = 0;
5238 AssociationIteratorTy(StmtPtrPtrTy E, TSIPtrPtrTy TSI, unsigned Offset,
5239 unsigned SelectedOffset)
5240 : E(E), TSI(TSI), Offset(Offset), SelectedOffset(SelectedOffset) {}
5241
5242 public:
5243 AssociationIteratorTy() : E(nullptr), TSI(nullptr) {}
5244 typename BaseTy::reference operator*() const {
5245 return AssociationTy<Const>(cast<Expr>(*E), *TSI,
5246 Offset == SelectedOffset);
5247 }
5248 typename BaseTy::pointer operator->() const { return **this; }
5249 using BaseTy::operator++;
5250 AssociationIteratorTy &operator++() {
5251 ++E;
5252 ++TSI;
5253 ++Offset;
5254 return *this;
5255 }
5256 bool operator==(AssociationIteratorTy Other) const { return E == Other.E; }
5257 }; // class AssociationIterator

5579/// PseudoObjectExpr - An expression which accesses a pseudo-object
5580/// l-value. A pseudo-object is an abstract object, accesses to which
5581/// are translated to calls. The pseudo-object expression has a
5582/// syntactic form, which shows how the expression was actually
5583/// written in the source code, and a semantic form, which is a series
5584/// of expressions to be executed in order which detail how the
5585/// operation is actually evaluated. Optionally, one of the semantic
5586/// forms may also provide a result value for the expression.
5587///
5588/// If any of the semantic-form expressions is an OpaqueValueExpr,
5589/// that OVE is required to have a source expression, and it is bound
5590/// to the result of that source expression. Such OVEs may appear
5591/// only in subsequent semantic-form expressions and as
5592/// sub-expressions of the syntactic form.
5593///
5594/// PseudoObjectExpr should be used only when an operation can be
5595/// usefully described in terms of fairly simple rewrite rules on
5596/// objects and functions that are meant to be used by end-developers.
5597/// For example, under the Itanium ABI, dynamic casts are implemented
5598/// as a call to a runtime function called __dynamic_cast; using this
5599/// class to describe that would be inappropriate because that call is
5600/// not really part of the user-visible semantics, and instead the
5601/// cast is properly reflected in the AST and IR-generation has been
5602/// taught to generate the call as necessary. In contrast, an
5603/// Objective-C property access is semantically defined to be
5604/// equivalent to a particular message send, and this is very much
5605/// part of the user model. The name of this class encourages this
5606/// modelling design.
5607class PseudoObjectExpr final
5608 : public Expr,
5609 private llvm::TrailingObjects<PseudoObjectExpr, Expr *> {
5610 // PseudoObjectExprBits.NumSubExprs - The number of sub-expressions.
5611 // Always at least two, because the first sub-expression is the
5612 // syntactic form.
5613
5614 // PseudoObjectExprBits.ResultIndex - The index of the
5615 // sub-expression holding the result. 0 means the result is void,
5616 // which is unambiguous because it's the index of the syntactic
5617 // form. Note that this is therefore 1 higher than the value passed
5618 // in to Create, which is an index within the semantic forms.
5619 // Note also that ASTStmtWriter assumes this encoding.
5620
5621 Expr **getSubExprsBuffer() { return getTrailingObjects<Expr *>(); }
5622 const Expr * const *getSubExprsBuffer() const {
5623 return getTrailingObjects<Expr *>();
5624 }
5625
5626 PseudoObjectExpr(QualType type, ExprValueKind VK,
5627 Expr *syntactic, ArrayRef<Expr*> semantic,
5628 unsigned resultIndex);
5629
5630 PseudoObjectExpr(EmptyShell shell, unsigned numSemanticExprs);
5631
5632 unsigned getNumSubExprs() const {
5633 return PseudoObjectExprBits.NumSubExprs;
5634 }
5635
5636public:
5637 /// NoResult - A value for the result index indicating that there is
5638 /// no semantic result.
5639 enum : unsigned { NoResult = ~0U };
5640
5641 static PseudoObjectExpr *Create(const ASTContext &Context, Expr *syntactic,
5642 ArrayRef<Expr*> semantic,
5643 unsigned resultIndex);
5644
5645 static PseudoObjectExpr *Create(const ASTContext &Context, EmptyShell shell,
5646 unsigned numSemanticExprs);
5647
5648 /// Return the syntactic form of this expression, i.e. the
5649 /// expression it actually looks like. Likely to be expressed in
5650 /// terms of OpaqueValueExprs bound in the semantic form.
5651 Expr *getSyntacticForm() { return getSubExprsBuffer()[0]; }
5652 const Expr *getSyntacticForm() const { return getSubExprsBuffer()[0]; }
5653
5654 /// Return the index of the result-bearing expression into the semantics
5655 /// expressions, or PseudoObjectExpr::NoResult if there is none.
5656 unsigned getResultExprIndex() const {
5657 if (PseudoObjectExprBits.ResultIndex == 0) return NoResult;
5658 return PseudoObjectExprBits.ResultIndex - 1;
5659 }
5660
5661 /// Return the result-bearing expression, or null if there is none.
5662 Expr *getResultExpr() {
5663 if (PseudoObjectExprBits.ResultIndex == 0)
5664 return nullptr;
5665 return getSubExprsBuffer()[PseudoObjectExprBits.ResultIndex];
5666 }
5667 const Expr *getResultExpr() const {
5668 return const_cast<PseudoObjectExpr*>(this)->getResultExpr();
5669 }
5670
5671 unsigned getNumSemanticExprs() const { return getNumSubExprs() - 1; }
5672
5673 typedef Expr * const *semantics_iterator;
5674 typedef const Expr * const *const_semantics_iterator;
5675 semantics_iterator semantics_begin() {
5676 return getSubExprsBuffer() + 1;
5677 }
5678 const_semantics_iterator semantics_begin() const {
5679 return getSubExprsBuffer() + 1;
5680 }
5681 semantics_iterator semantics_end() {
5682 return getSubExprsBuffer() + getNumSubExprs();
5683 }
5684 const_semantics_iterator semantics_end() const {
5685 return getSubExprsBuffer() + getNumSubExprs();
5686 }
5687
5688 llvm::iterator_range<semantics_iterator> semantics() {
5689 return llvm::make_range(semantics_begin(), semantics_end());
5690 }
5691 llvm::iterator_range<const_semantics_iterator> semantics() const {
5692 return llvm::make_range(semantics_begin(), semantics_end());
5693 }
5694
5695 Expr *getSemanticExpr(unsigned index) {
5696 assert(index + 1 < getNumSubExprs());
5697 return getSubExprsBuffer()[index + 1];
5698 }
5699 const Expr *getSemanticExpr(unsigned index) const {
5700 return const_cast<PseudoObjectExpr*>(this)->getSemanticExpr(index);
5701 }
5702
5703 SourceLocation getExprLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
5704 return getSyntacticForm()->getExprLoc();
5705 }
5706
5707 SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
5708 return getSyntacticForm()->getBeginLoc();
5709 }
5710 SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
5711 return getSyntacticForm()->getEndLoc();
5712 }
5713
5714 child_range children() {
5715 const_child_range CCR =
5716 const_cast<const PseudoObjectExpr *>(this)->children();
5717 return child_range(cast_away_const(CCR.begin()),
5718 cast_away_const(CCR.end()));
5719 }
5720 const_child_range children() const {
5721 Stmt *const *cs = const_cast<Stmt *const *>(
5722 reinterpret_cast<const Stmt *const *>(getSubExprsBuffer()));
5723 return const_child_range(cs, cs + getNumSubExprs());
5724 }
5725
5726 static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
5727 return T->getStmtClass() == PseudoObjectExprClass;
5728 }
5729
5730 friend TrailingObjects;
5731 friend class ASTStmtReader;
5732};

5734/// AtomicExpr - Variadic atomic builtins: __atomic_exchange, __atomic_fetch_*,
5735/// __atomic_load, __atomic_store, and __atomic_compare_exchange_*, for the
5736/// similarly-named C++11 instructions, and __c11 variants for <stdatomic.h>,
5737/// and corresponding __opencl_atomic_* for OpenCL 2.0.
5738/// All of these instructions take one primary pointer, at least one memory
5739/// order. The instructions for which getScopeModel returns non-null value
5740/// take one synch scope.
5741class AtomicExpr : public Expr {
5742public:
5743 enum AtomicOp {
5744#define BUILTIN(ID, TYPE, ATTRS)
5745#define ATOMIC_BUILTIN(ID, TYPE, ATTRS) AO ## ID,
5746#include "clang/Basic/Builtins.def"
5747 // Avoid trailing comma
5748 BI_First = 0
5749 };
5750
5751private:
5752 /// Location of sub-expressions.
5753 /// The location of Scope sub-expression is NumSubExprs - 1, which is
5754 /// not fixed, therefore is not defined in enum.
5755 enum { PTR, ORDER, VAL1, ORDER_FAIL, VAL2, WEAK, END_EXPR };
5756 Stmt *SubExprs[END_EXPR + 1];
5757 unsigned NumSubExprs;
5758 SourceLocation BuiltinLoc, RParenLoc;
5759 AtomicOp Op;
5760
5761 friend class ASTStmtReader;
5762public:
5763 AtomicExpr(SourceLocation BLoc, ArrayRef<Expr*> args, QualType t,
5764 AtomicOp op, SourceLocation RP);
5765
5766 /// Determine the number of arguments the specified atomic builtin
5767 /// should have.
5768 static unsigned getNumSubExprs(AtomicOp Op);
5769
5770 /// Build an empty AtomicExpr.
5771 explicit AtomicExpr(EmptyShell Empty) : Expr(AtomicExprClass, Empty) { }
5772
5773 Expr *getPtr() const {
5774 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[PTR]);
5775 }
5776 Expr *getOrder() const {
5777 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[ORDER]);
5778 }
5779 Expr *getScope() const {
5780 assert(getScopeModel() && "No scope");
5781 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[NumSubExprs - 1]);
5782 }
5783 Expr *getVal1() const {
5784 if (Op == AO__c11_atomic_init || Op == AO__opencl_atomic_init)
5785 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[ORDER]);
5786 assert(NumSubExprs > VAL1);
5787 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[VAL1]);
5788 }
5789 Expr *getOrderFail() const {
5790 assert(NumSubExprs > ORDER_FAIL);
5791 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[ORDER_FAIL]);
5792 }
5793 Expr *getVal2() const {
5794 if (Op == AO__atomic_exchange)
5795 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[ORDER_FAIL]);
5796 assert(NumSubExprs > VAL2);
5797 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[VAL2]);
5798 }
5799 Expr *getWeak() const {
5800 assert(NumSubExprs > WEAK);
5801 return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[WEAK]);
5802 }
5803 QualType getValueType() const;
5804
5805 AtomicOp getOp() const { return Op; }
5806 unsigned getNumSubExprs() const { return NumSubExprs; }
5807
5808 Expr **getSubExprs() { return reinterpret_cast<Expr **>(SubExprs); }
5809 const Expr * const *getSubExprs() const {
5810 return reinterpret_cast<Expr * const *>(SubExprs);
5811 }
5812
5813 bool isVolatile() const {
5814 return getPtr()->getType()->getPointeeType().isVolatileQualified();
5815 }
5816
5817 bool isCmpXChg() const {
5818 return getOp() == AO__c11_atomic_compare_exchange_strong ||
5819 getOp() == AO__c11_atomic_compare_exchange_weak ||
5820 getOp() == AO__opencl_atomic_compare_exchange_strong ||
5821 getOp() == AO__opencl_atomic_compare_exchange_weak ||
5822 getOp() == AO__atomic_compare_exchange ||
5823 getOp() == AO__atomic_compare_exchange_n;
5824 }
5825
5826 bool isOpenCL() const {
5827 return getOp() >= AO__opencl_atomic_init &&
5828 getOp() <= AO__opencl_atomic_fetch_max;
5829 }
5830
5831 SourceLocation getBuiltinLoc() const { return BuiltinLoc; }
5832 SourceLocation getRParenLoc() const { return RParenLoc; }
5833
5834 SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return BuiltinLoc; }
5835 SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return RParenLoc; }
5836
5837 static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
5838 return T->getStmtClass() == AtomicExprClass;
5839 }
5840
5841 // Iterators
5842 child_range children() {
5843 return child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs+NumSubExprs);
5844 }
5845 const_child_range children() const {
5846 return const_child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + NumSubExprs);
5847 }
5848
5849 /// Get atomic scope model for the atomic op code.
5850 /// \return empty atomic scope model if the atomic op code does not have
5851 /// scope operand.
5852 static std::unique_ptr<AtomicScopeModel> getScopeModel(AtomicOp Op) {
5853 auto Kind =
5854 (Op >= AO__opencl_atomic_load && Op <= AO__opencl_atomic_fetch_max)
5855 ? AtomicScopeModelKind::OpenCL
5856 : AtomicScopeModelKind::None;
5857 return AtomicScopeModel::create(Kind);
5858 }
5859
5860 /// Get atomic scope model.
5861 /// \return empty atomic scope model if this atomic expression does not have
5862 /// scope operand.
5863 std::unique_ptr<AtomicScopeModel> getScopeModel() const {
5864 return getScopeModel(getOp());
5865 }
5866};
